#JAVA BASICS
Java’s biggest claim to fame is WORA: Write Once, Run Anywhere.
Unlike languages that compile directly into machine code for a specific operating system (like C++), Java compiles into an intermediate format called Bytecode. 
Any device with a Java Virtual Machine (JVM) can run this bytecode.
The Holy Trinity of Java: JVM, JRE, and JDK
   JVM (Java Virtual Machine): The engine that actually runs the Java bytecode.
   JRE (Java Runtime Environment): The toolkit needed to run Java programs. It includes the JVM plus core libraries.
   JDK (Java Development Kit): The full developer setup. It includes the JRE plus development tools like the compiler (javac).


#CONTROL STATEMENTS
In Java, Control Statements are the steering wheel of your code. By default, code executes line by line, from top to bottom.
Control statements break this linear flow, allowing your program to make decisions, repeat actions, or jump to different sections based on conditions.
They are divided into three main categories:
  Decision-Making (Selection) Statements
  Looping (Iteration) Statements
  Jump Statements

1. Decision-Making Statements
  These statements evaluate a boolean condition (true or false) and decide which block of code to run next.
  A. The if-else Hierarchy
      Simple if: Executes a block of code only if the condition is true.
      if-else: Gives an alternative block of code if the condition is false.
      if-else if ladder: Tests multiple conditions in sequence. The first one that evaluates to true executes, and the rest are skipped.
      Nested if: An if statement inside another if statement, used for multi-layered conditions.
 B. The switch Statement
     Instead of writing dozens of if-else statements, switch tests a single variable against a list of explicit values (called cases).
     The break keyword: Crucial in a switch. If you omit break, the program will "fall through" and execute all subsequent cases regardless of whether they match.
     The default case: Acts like the final else; it executes if none of the cases match.
     Allowed types: byte, short, char, int, String, and Enums.

2. Looping (Iteration) Statements
   Loops allow you to execute a block of code repeatedly as long as a specified condition remains true.
   Every loop requires three core components to prevent an infinite loop: Initialization (starting point), Condition (stop criterion), and Increment/Decrement (step size).
  A. for Loop
    Best used when you know in advance exactly how many times the loop should run.
    Syntax structure: for(initialization; condition; increment/decrement) { ... }
  B. Enhanced for Loop (For-Each)
     Introduced to strictly iterate through elements of an array or a collection without using an explicit counter or index. It is cleaner and prevents "off-by-one" errors.
  C. while Loop
    Best used when you do not know the exact number of iterations beforehand, but you know the condition that must be met to stop. 
      It checks the condition before executing the loop body (Entry-controlled loop).
  D. do-while Loop
    Similar to the while loop, but with one major difference: it checks the condition after executing the loop body (Exit-controlled loop).
    Because of this, a do-while loop is guaranteed to run at least once, even if the condition is false right from the start.

3. Jump Statements
    Jump statements unconditionally transfer the control of execution from one part of the program to another.
    break: Instantly terminates the loop or switch statement entirely and moves to the next line of code immediately following the block.
    continue: Skips the current iteration of a loop and jumps straight to the next evaluation/increment step. It does not stop the whole loop, just the current round.
    return: Explicitly returns from a method. It stops executing the entire method and passes control back to whoever called it.
#Operators
   In Java, Operators are special symbols that perform specific operations on one, two, or three operands (variables or values) and then return a result.
1. By the Number of Operands
   Unary Operators: Work on a single operand (e.g., ++a).
   Binary Operators: Work on two operands (e.g., a + b). Most Java operators fall into this category.
   Ternary Operator: Works on three operands (e.g., condition ? trueValue : falseValue).
2. Functional Categories of Operators
   A. Arithmetic Operators (The Math Toolkit)
      Used to perform basic mathematical operations.
      + (Addition)
      - (Subtraction)
      * (Multiplication)
      / (Division) — Note: If both operands are integers, this performs integer division and drops the remainder (e.g., 5 / 2 is 2, not 2.5).
      % (Modulus) — Returns the remainder of a division (e.g., 5 % 2 is 1).
   B. Unary Operators
      These require only one operand and are used to increment, decrement, or invert a value.
      ++ (Increment): Increases the value by 1.
      -- (Decrement): Decreases the value by 1.
      Prefix (++x): Increments the value before using it in the expression.
      Postfix (x++): Uses the current value in the expression first, then increments it.
      ! (Logical Complement): Inverts a boolean value (e.g., !true becomes false).

  C. Relational (Comparison) Operators
      Used to compare two values. They always return a boolean value (true or false). They are the backbone of your conditional statements (if conditions).
      == (Equal to) — Don't confuse this with the single = assignment operator!
      != (Not equal to)
      > (Greater than)
      < (Less than)
      >= (Greater than or equal to)
      <= (Less than or equal to)
  D. Logical Operators
      Used to combine multiple boolean expressions together. They use short-circuit evaluation, meaning they stop evaluating as soon as the final outcome is certain.
      && (Logical AND): Returns true only if both conditions are true. If the first condition is false, Java doesn't even bother checking the second one.
      || (Logical OR): Returns true if at least one condition is true. If the first condition is true, it skips checking the second one.
  E. Assignment Operators
      Used to assign values to variables.
      = (Simple Assignment): Assigns the value on the right to the variable on the left.
      Compound Assignments (+=, -=, *=, /=, %=): Shortcuts that perform an operation and assign the result in one step.
      x += 5; is exactly the same as writing x = x + 5;
 F. Bitwise Operators (Advanced)
      These perform operations directly on the individual bits (0s and 1s) of integer types.
      & (Bitwise AND), | (Bitwise OR), ^ (Bitwise XOR), ~ (Bitwise Complement).
      << (Left shift), >> (Right shift).

3. Operator Precedence (Order of Operations)
      Just like in mathematics, Java evaluates operators in a specific order. For example, multiplication happens before addition.
      If you want to override the default precedence or just want to make your code easier to read, always use parentheses (). 
      Parentheses have the highest precedence in Java.



















